        <blockquote>
        <p><em>Composition and Design:</em> 2 - Ambitious but could be done much better. There are a lot of different elements in here all vying for our attention perhaps more or less than they should be. The girl and her face especially should be larger and more of a focal point, and things like her basket of apples and so on could be smaller in comparison. I like the POV aspect though, the floorboards and footprints etc help with the depth a bit, the lighting being centred is a good idea but I think having an actual source for it might help sell things better, say if it was from an open window or skylight or something. </p>
        <p><em>Application of other Artistic Fundamentals:</em> 1 - There's evidence of the fundamentals here; perspective, depth, leading the eye, texture etc, but things need worked on some more. You gave yourself so much to do with this and no doubt didn't have enough time to finish up everything, maybe better pacing of yourself is a good thing to focus on for the next prompt. The claws are pretty nice, I like the colour change and the attention to texture. The girl herself and things like the body in the background bring the rest of the piece down though, and the overall design things mentioned already. If it had been much simpler it might have been less ambitious, but would have given you more time to really work on things and bring up the overall quality. </p>
        <p><em>Creativity and Originality:</em> 2 - The idea is solid tbh, the POV aspect is an unusual take and having the girl's face and horror be the centre point is a good idea, especially for dark fairy tales that's a very key part of the story. I think more thought into lighting etc would have helped, whcih again if this piece was simpler overall, like just the hands and the girl even, you would be able to focus on designing those parts more.</p>
        <p><em>Materials and Media:</em> 1 - You made some good uses of the medium, like the colour change on the claws or the soft brushes for lighting, but there's much you can still learn. I would reccomend practicing working from big shapes to small shapes more slowly, if you switch to a small detailing brush too soon like you seem to have done with the claws or the girl's hair, you give yourself a lot more work to do and it also doesn't read as well. I hope you can pace things better for the next prompt and show what a simpler but more finished piece would look like.</p>
