        <p><em>Composition and Design:</em> 3 - The spiral composition is a good idea, but there just needed to be more to it. more branches splitting off from the main mass, more feathers, or just something else to fill in the white void woud have been great. </p>
        <p><em>Application of other Artistic Fundamentals:</em> 2 - You leant into the strength of Hard black shows fairly well, but those shadows are still very rough. Hard shadows like the ones you went for tend to work best when the edge of the shadow is just as hard, Mike Mignola's art is a great example of this, where shadows are generally seperated by very strong, bold lines. Try and make your designs work with those hard shadows a bit more in the future, use those shadows to indicate plane changes and depth. Its hard to really crit the fox because controlling your lines when drawing small characters is tough. all i can really tell you to do is to try and be as precise as you can, and eventually youll be able to cram more fine details in those smaller drawings.</p>
        <p><em>Creativity and Originality:</em> 3 - most of the creative value here is from the composition itself, so what i said there applies here. its a good comp, but theres just not a lot here to talk about, just a single spiral, a fox and a crow along the spirals path. </p>
        <p><em>Materials and Media:</em> 1 - Your lines are pretty shakey, but there are ways to mitigate that. when drawing curved structures like tree trunks, its okay to speed up a bit. drawing lines a bit faster can make getting good lines a lot easier. you can think of line quality the same way as riding a bike in some senses, as in, if you ride a bike very slowly its very hard to stay on a straight line, but if you go a bit faster, you are suddenly moving along a straighter path. the same thing happens with your lines depending on how fast you do them. just dont rush yourself either. rushing always makes things worse.</p>
