        <h2 class="blog-post-title">jozu</h2>
        <strong>Panelist: Choob </strong>
        <blockquote>
        <p><em>Composition and Design:</em>2 - It tells some good story and I like the feeling of us being comfortable inside while the wolf shouts from outside. I feel like there should be more emphasis placed on the two pigs nearest to us though, they shouldnt be quite as cropped off as they are and could do with being a different value to bring them forward out of their surroundings. Darkening the back wall would also help with this. And while I love the /ic/ pig, he has as much space given to him as the other people in the scene which makes me unsure if he's the focal point or if the wolf or other pigs are.</p>
        <p><em>Application of other Artistic Fundamentals:</em>2 - There's some really nice details, like the fur on the wolf's face, a lot of the rest is left pretty bare though. Some shadows on the furniture would help give them some more perspective and make it feel more like a 3D scene, and the pigs closest to us could do with some more detailing too since they're nearer to us than the ic pig. Thinking about perspective more would be good too, I think we would see more of the top of the table between the two pigs from this angle and seeing that and the items on top of it would help sell the perspective more too. More colour variation would be nice too, even simple things like how pigs are more reddish around the ears and nose, and paler on most of the rest of the face. There's some of this there but you've changed more the value and not the hue or saturation as much, don't be afraid to try things out on a different layer and then tone them down as needed. </p>
        <p><em>Creativity and Originality:</em> 3 - I've never seen this story like this in my life. More details of the room and items in it would be great, and some more design to the characters to make the pigs more different, but the idea itself is great and ofc topical. </p>
        <p><em>Materials and Media:</em> 1 - I'd like to see more experimenting with different brushes and ways of implying texture and form like you did with the wolf's face. Using different edges or having gradients of different colour could really help with things like the pigs fleshy bodies, and you can do that in different ways, it doesnt have to all be brushed in manually. </p>
